{"title_page": "2013 in North-American radio", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|2013|radio|music|television|home video}}\n\nThe following is a list of events affecting [[radio broadcasting]] in '''2013'''. Events listed include radio program debuts, finales, cancellations, and station launches, closures and format changes, as well as information about controversies.\n\n==Notable events==\n\n===January===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''1'''\n|[[WEZQ]]/[[Bangor, Maine]] flips from AC to Sports as \"92.9 The Ticket.\" The station will be an affiliate of [[ESPN Radio]] but will use live staffers throughout the day.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/79978/wezq-punching-its-ticket-for-sports/ \"WEZQ Punching Its Ticket For Sports\"] from Radio Insight (December 12, 2012)</ref>\n|-\n|Service Broadcasting sells [[KKDA (AM)|KKDA-AM]]/[[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] to SKR properties, who immediately take over the station under a LMA and flip it to Korean programming after 43 years as a R&B-focused outlet serving the African American community through its various incarnations.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80271/soul-730-dallas-sold/ \"Soul 730 Dallas Sold; Drops Format\"] from Radio Insight (January 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Clear Channel Communications]] flips two of their [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]/[[Visalia, California]] properties, [[Fox Sports Radio]] affiliate [[KRZR]] and Adult Top 40 [[KALZ]], to a Talk radio simulcast as \"Power Talk 1400 & 96.7,\" using programming from co-owned [[Premiere Radio Networks]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/70732/major-fresno-talk-sports-shuffle-coming/ \"PowerTalk 96.7 Debuts In Fresno\"] from Radio Insight (January 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|Just weeks after letting go most of its airstaff, WTKK/[[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] ended its Talk format to begin a series of format stunts, which landed on [[Rhythmic contemporary|Rhythmic AC]] as \"Hot 96.9\" on January 8. The station eventually took the call sign [[WBQT (FM)|WBQT]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/79932/whos-dropping-a-beat-into-boston/ \"Who\u2019s Dropping A Beat Into Boston?\"] from Radio Insight (December 28, 2012)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''3'''\n|[[Cumulus Media]] reached a deal with [[Arbitron]] to have its stations now included in Arbitron ratings and PPMs after a three-year absence, which also include sharing media and research content between the two companies.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/113794/cumulus-signs-multi-year-contract-with-arbitron \"Cumulus Signs Multi-Year Contract With Arbitron\"] from All Access (January 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Curtis Media flips Regional Mexican WYMY/[[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] to Urban AC with the new calls [[WWPL|WBZJ]]<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/80104/curtis-media-to-launch-new-raleigh-ac/ \"Curtis Media Launches 96.9 WBZJ Raleigh\"] from Radio Insight (January 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|[[WOKY]]/[[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] ends its 4-year run at Classic Country (following [[WNRG-FM|WZBK]]'s departure from the same format in September 2012) to enter the market's Sports Talk battle with [[WSSP]] and [[WAUK]], using programming from [[Fox Sports Radio]] and [[NBC Sports Radio]] as well as simulcasts of programs from sister station [[WTSO]]/[[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]].<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/185446641.html WOKY-AM changes to all sports talk format] from ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', January 2, 2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|[[CKNG-FM|CKNG]]/[[Edmonton]] drops Classic Hits for Adult Top 40 as \"92.5 Fresh FM\".<ref>[http://rwcrn.com/edmontons-joe-fm-flips-to-fresh-fm Edmonton\u2019s JOE FM flips to FRESH FM] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114050048/http://rwcrn.com/edmontons-joe-fm-flips-to-fresh-fm |date=2013-01-14 }} from ''Radio West / Canadian Radio News'', January 9, 2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''10'''\n|Crain Media makes a series of shuffles in [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], with [[KKSP]] shifting to Sports and relocating its Talk format to 96.5, replacing Top 40/CHR [[KHTE-FM|KHTE]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80409/fresh-talk-93-3-little-rock-to-move-pave-way-for-more-sports/ Fresh Talk 93.3 Little Rock To Move; Pave Way For More Sports] from Radio Insight, January 7, 2013</ref>\n|-\n|[[CBS Radio]] signs up with [[TuneIn]] to place their radio stations on TuneIn's platform. The move will not affect CBS's Radio.com platform, which will continue featuring the stations.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/114078/tunein-expands-deal-with-cbs-radio-to-stream-music \"TuneIn Expands Deal With CBS Radio To Stream Music Stations\"] from All Access (January 10, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''11'''\n|[[WNSH|WFME]]/[[Newark, New Jersey]] ends [[Family Radio]] programming as it comes under the control of [[Cumulus Media]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fybush |first=Scott |url=http://www.fybush.com/nerw-20130114/ |title=NERW 1/14/13: After 47 Years, WFME Flips |publisher=Fybush.com |date=2013-01-14 |accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref>  After a week of [[stunting (broadcasting)|stunting]], the rechristened WRXP launches with a [[country music]] format on January 21, returning country to the [[New York City]] market after a 17-year absence, as well as making WRXP the first station to adopt Cumulus' \"Nash FM\" country music branding. (WRXP would swap its call sign for the WNSH calls from its [[Cambridge, Minnesota]] sister station on January 29.)<ref>[http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=2607696 \"Cumulus Announces National \"Nash\" Brand For Country Entertainment,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106040511/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=2607696 |date=2013-11-06 }} from FMQB, 1/22/2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''25'''\n|In an effort to boost its ratings (as they continue to trail Rhythmic Top 40 [[WNVZ]] and Top 40/CHR [[WVHT]] in the [[Arbitrons]] after nine months), Top 40/CHR WVMA/[[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]] rebrands from \"New 105.3\" to \"Now 105.3\",<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80702/new-is-now-in-norfolk/ \"New Is Now In Norfolk\"] from Radio Insight (January 25, 2013)</ref> eventually changing its call letters to [[WNOH]].\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[WKTU]]/New York afternoon host and syndicated air personality [[Sean Hamilton|Hollywood Hamilton]] signs a new deal with [[Premiere Networks]] that brings his syndicated countdown shows (The Mainstream and Rhythmic versions of ''Weekend Top 30'' and ''Remix Top 30'') into the Premiere syndication stable beginning February 1. In addition, his shows will also be featured on the [[iHeartRadio]] platform, which is owned by Premiere's parent company (and Hamilton's employer) [[Clear Channel Communications]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/114669/hollywood-hamilton-joins-premiere-networks-nationa \"Hollywood Hamilton Joins Premiere Networks National Lineup\"] from All Access (January 28, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===February===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|[[Journal Communications]] Top 40/CHR [[KSPW]]/[[Springfield, Missouri|Springfield]] fired PD/afternoon host Simon Nytes after learning that he lied about having served in the military. This comes after an Army veteran had visited the studios on February 5 and questioned Nytes' claim after an employee at the studio told him about Nytes' Army background, which he would later [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fKOWKoKP6uk post the same day] on [[YouTube]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/115101/kspw-s-simon-nytes-fired-after-faking-being-in-mil KSPW's Simon Nytes Fired After Faking Being In Military] from All Access (February 7, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''8'''\n|[[Premiere Networks]]' ''The [[Bobby Bones Show]]'' airs its last morning program for Top 40/CHR stations, as it makes the transition to a syndicated morning program for Country stations beginning February 18.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80805/bobby-bones-moves-from-chr-to-country/ Bobby Bones Moves From CHR To Country] from Radio Insight (February 4, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[iHeartRadio]] expands the EDM-formatted \"Evolution\" platform to Los Angeles, where it replaces the in-house Dance/Club Hits-formatted \"Club KIIS\" platform on the HD2 subchannel of Top 40/CHR [[KIIS-FM]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/115155/ccm-e-brings-edm-evolution-to-kiis-hd2 \"CCM+E Brings EDM 'Evolution' To KIIS HD2\"] from All Access (February 8, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|[[WMVY]]/[[Tisbury, Massachusetts]] moves its [[adult album alternative]] format exclusively to [[Internet radio]], after Aritaur Communications sells the station's 92.7 FM facility to [[Boston University]], which relaunches it as WBUA, a satellite of [[WBUR|WBUR-FM]]/[[Boston]]. The Internet-only version of WMVY is operated by a nonprofit group, Friends of mvyradio, which is separate from Aritaur and unrelated to WBUR.<ref name=mvt-wbualaunch>{{cite news|title=WBUR will begin broadcasting on 92.7 FM at midnight Friday|url=http://www.mvtimes.com/2013/02/06/wbur-will-begin-broadcasting-927-fm-midnight-friday-14366/|accessdate=February 9, 2013|newspaper=The Martha's Vineyard Times|date=February 6, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.wbur.org/2012/11/27/wmvy-online-support \"After WBUR Purchase, Martha\u2019s Vineyard Station WMVY May Move Online\"], WBUR website</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''12'''\n|[[Cox Communications]] spins off their radio properties to different companies as part of their plan to consolidate their combined TV and radio clusters in Cox's portfolio and sell off TV and radio clusters that are not paired up in, with the stations in Southern [[Connecticut]] going to Connoisseur Media and its [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greeenville]], [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|Honolulu]], [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] clusters going to Summit Media.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/115266/cox-media-sells-6-market-clusters-to-two-radio-gro Cox Media Sells 6 Market Clusters To Two Radio Groups] from All Access (February 12, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14'''\n|[[KYWD|KNST-FM]]/[[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]] flips from a simulcast of its [[KNST|News/Talk AM sister station]] to Country as \"Wild Country 97.1.\"<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/115351/knst-flips-to-country-as-wild-country-97-1-bones-f KNST Flips To Country As \u2018Wild Country 97.1,\u2019 Bones For Mornings] from All Access (February 14, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''22'''\n|After six months as a Rhythmic, [[KRPT]]/[[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]] flips to Classic Country as \"K-BUC 92.5.\" The Rhythmic format continues on its translator at 105.7.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80995/92-5-k-buc-debuts-in-san-antonio/ \"92.5 K-BUC Debuts In San Antonio\"] from Radio Insight (February 22, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''25'''\n|[[CBS Radio]] sells Urban AC [[WUUB]]/[[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]] to Good Karma Broadcasting, who in turn immediately flip the station to a simulcast of [[ESPN Radio]] affiliate [[WEFL]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81006/good-karma-acquires-flips-wuub-west-palm-beach/ \"Good Karma Acquires & Flips WUUB West Palm Beach\"] from Radio Insight (February 25, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''26'''\n|Citing a decade of financial losses they had with an African-American talk radio format, [[WZTI|WMCS]]/[[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] dropped the format and starts [[stunting (broadcasting)|stunting]], adopting an adult standards format at the end of the week.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81050/wmcs-milwaukee-abandons-black-talk/ \"WMCS Milwaukee Abandons Black Talk\"] from Radio Insight (February 26, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===March===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"5\"|'''1'''\n|African-American talk outlet [[KSHJ|KCOH]]/[[Houston, Texas|Houston]] relocates from its longtime home at 1430 to 1230, displacing Regional Mexican [[KCOH|KQUE]] under a leasing agreement between KCOH's new owner Jeese Dunn and KQUE's licensee [[Liberman Broadcasting]]. The new occupant and owner of the 1430 frequency, La Promesa Foundation, launched a Catholic programming format the same day.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80036/kcoh-houston-to-relocate/ \"KCOH Houston Relocates\"] From Radio Insight (March 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WRTH (FM)|WOLT]]/[[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]] exits the part-time Dance Top 40/part-time brokered programming format to pick up the Oldies format from AM sister [[WOLI (AM)|WOLI/W289BS]], who in turn takes the brokered programming with Adult Standards filling in most of the other dayparts.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/80914/earth-is-moving-in-greenvillespartanburg/ \"Earth Is Moving In Greenville/Spartanburg\"] from Radio Insight (March 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|After 5 months in the format, [[Florence, South Carolina]] Rhythmic oldies trio [[WOLH]]/[[WHYM|WHYM & W255BD]] flipped to [[ESPN Radio]], bringing that Sports Talk network back after former affiliate [[WWFN-FM|WWFN]] switched to [[CBS Sports Radio]] in January.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81085/espn-radio-returns-to-florence/ \"ESPN Radio Returns To Florence\"] from Radio Insight (March 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|The FCC accepts a proposal that would see a signal upgrade for [[WSOS-FM|WSOS]]/[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] from Class C3 to C2. If approved, it would require two Class C stations in [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[WQBT]] and [[WIXV]], to switch their signals.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81092/fcc-report-31-jacksonville-upgrade-could-lead-to-savannah-shuffle/ \"FCC Report 3/1: Jacksonville Upgrade Could Lead To Savannah Shuffle\"] from Radio Insight (March 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Classic rock/classic hits 92.3 Fred FM [[CFRK-FM]] in [[Fredericton, New Brunswick|Fredericton]] abruptly makes its exit as it flips to Top 40/CHR as Hot 92.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''3'''\n|[[KMVX|KNOE-FM]]/[[Monroe, Louisiana]] drops Top 40/CHR for Urban AC as \"Mix 101.9\".<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81104/star-101-9-monroe-flips-to-urban-ac/ \"Star 101.9 Monroe Flips To Urban AC\"] from Radio Insight (March 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''4'''\n|After seeing their first proposal turned down by the CRTC in October 2012, Canada's [[Bell Media]] and [[Astral Media]] are given a greenlight by the country's Competition Bureau, paving the way for the two companies to resume their merger, but on the condition that agree to spin-off and swap several radio and TV properties, as well as allowing other broadcasters to have partial stakes in their other media properties.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81118/bellastral-merger-take-2-two-ottawa-stations-sold/ \"Bell/Astral Merger Take 2; Two Ottawa Stations Sold\"] from Radio Insight (March 4, 2013)</ref>  The [[Canadian Radio-Television and Telecommunications Commission|CRTC]] approves the deal on June 27, and Bell formally acquires Astral on July 5.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2013/06/27/business-bell-astral-crtc-decision.html \"CRTC approves Bell-Astral merger], from CBC News, 6/27/2013</ref>\n|-\n|[[WNRS (AM)|WNRS]]/[[Herkimer, New York]] switches from its variety sports/business talk format to ''[[The True Oldies Channel]]''.<ref>Maughton, Peter (March 8, 2013). [http://www.cnyradio.com/2013/03/08/true-oldies-channel-replaces-fox-sports-bloomberg-biz-on-wnrs/ True Oldies Channel replaces Fox Sports & Bloomberg Biz on WNRS]. ''CNYRadio.com''. Retrieved March 10, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''11'''\n|[[Miami, Florida|Miami]] once again has a Dance outlet, as Clear Channel expands the \"Evolution\" brand to its translator at 93.5, [[WIOD#Evolution 93.5 FM|W228BY]]. The launch coincides with the [[Winter Music Conference]] and the [[Ultra Music Festival]], whose events take place every March during this time.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81189/miami-reaches-an-evolutionary-state/ \"Miami Reaches An Evolutionary State\"] from Radio Insight (March 12, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14'''\n|[[Sirius XM Radio]] removes [[Playboy Radio]] from its lineup, with the station continuing as an independent online website.<ref>[http://www.sirius.com/playboyradio Message from Playboy Radio on SiriusXM] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110106084458/http://www.sirius.com/playboyradio |date=2011-01-06 }} (March 14, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''26'''\n|Smooth Jazz [[WAUN-FM]] and their translators bring the [[Regional Mexican]] format to the [[Green Bay, Wisconsin]] radio market for the first time.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81310/smooth-bays-shifts-to-regional-mexican/ Smooth Bays Shifts To Regional Mexican] from Radio Insight (March 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WKIO|WUIL]]/[[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]] flips from Active Rock to Classic Hits and brings back the call letters of WKIO, which has heritage in the market from 1978 to 2005 [[WREE|at 92.5]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81272/urock-champaign-urbana-to-rock-no-more/ URock Champaign-Urbana Shifts To Classic Hits] from Radio Insight (March 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|Clear Channel flips [[Atlanta]] stations [[WRDA (FM)|WWVA-FM]] and [[WRDG|WWLG]] from Rhythmic Top 40 to Alternative Rock.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81343/alternative-on-its-way-back-to-atlanta/ Alternative Returns To Atlanta] from Radio Insight (March 28, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===April===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=5|'''1'''\n|The AC format once again goes away in the Minneapolis-St. Paul radio market, as the trimulcast of [[WGVX|WGVX/WRXP/WGVZ]] flips to Sports as \"The Ticket\"; the [[CBS Sports Radio]] affiliate brings the number of Sports outlets in the Twin Cities to three, joining incumbents [[KFXN-FM]] and [[KSTP (AM)|KSTP]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/116946/minneapolis-gets-more-sports-on-105-the-ticket \"Minneapolis Gets More Sports On '105 The Ticket'\"] from All Access (April 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WRNB]]/[[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] drops Urban AC for Rhythmic Oldies as \"Old School 100.3.\"<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/116944/wrnb-flipping-from-urban-ac-to-old-school \"WRNB Flipping From Urban AC to Old School\"] from All Access (April 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|The 5-way Top 40 war in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]] see a surprise shakeup, as American General Media switched the dial positions of Top 40/CHR [[KVCN|KDLW]] and Rhythmic Top 40 sister [[KDLW|KAGM]] (KDLW broadcasts at 106.7 and assigned to [[Los Alamos, New Mexico|Los Alamos]], but has clear coverage in the metro from the north at 43&nbsp;kW that also covers [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]]; KAGM broadcasts at 106.3 and licensed to [[Los Lunas, New Mexico|Los Lunas]] with 98&nbsp;kW but has a somewhat semi-static signal coverage due to its transmitter being 30 miles away from the south). AGM also rebranded the monikers of KDLW as \"Z106.3 Hit Music Now\" and KAGM as \"Power 106.7\" the same day.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81384/omg-power-makes-a-move-in-albuquerque/ \"OMG! Power Makes A Move In Albuquerque\"] From Radio Insight (March 28, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Two presenters at [[WWGR]] in [[Lee County, Florida]], who told listeners \"[[dihydrogen monoxide hoax|dihydrogen monoxide]]\" was coming out of their water taps as part of an [[April Fool's Day]] hoax, are suspended indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/04/presenters-suspended-for-april-fool-hoax/ |title=Presenters suspended for April Fool hoax |publisher=Radio Today |date=April 1, 2013 |accessdate=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|Clear Channel's [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] cluster makes a pair of call letter adjustments, with the [[WRDU]] calls moving from 106.1 to 100.7 and relaunched it as \"Classic Rock 100.7\" (replacing the WRVA and its \"100.7 The River\" moniker), while giving its Talk sister at 106.1 the [[WTKK]] calls (that [[WBQT (FM)|WBQT]]/Boston gave up back in January) and rebrands it from \"[[Rush Limbaugh|Rush]] Radio\" to \"106.1FM WTKK.\"<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/116979/call-letter-swap-puts-wrdu-on-classic-rock-100-7-w \"Call Letter Swap Puts WRDU On 'Classic Rock 100.7,' WTKK On Former 'Rush Radio 106.1'\"] from All Access (April 2, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''3'''\n|After nearly two years with an interactive Rhythmic presentation that featured Hip-Hop, [[WRDF|WHPP]]/[[Fort Wayne, Indiana|Ft. Wayne]] become that format's latest casualty as it flips to [[1990s in music|'90s based Pop Music]] as \"Rewind 106.3.\" The Hip-Hop format moves over to the internet.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/117027/rewind-106-3-coming-to-ft-wayne \"Rewind 106.3 Coming To Ft. Wayne\"] from All Access (April 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''4'''\n|The [[Cape Cod]] region of [[Massachusetts]] picks up its first Rhythmic Top 40 outlet, as [[WHYA]] splits from a simulcast of Adult Hits sister [[WFRQ]] to become \"Y101.1, The Beat of Cape Cod.\"<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/117092/codcomm-flips-to-top-40-on-whya-as-y101 \"CodComm Flips To Top 40 On WHYA As Y101\"] from All Access (April 4, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|[[Educational Media Foundation]] acquires another commercial outlet with the purchase of Country [[KXAI|KOUL]]/[[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] from Tejas Broadcasting. KOUL will become an [[Air1]] station after the sale closes.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81544/emf-acquires-koul-corpus-christi/ \"EMF Acquires KOUL Corpus Christi\"] from Radio-Insight (April 5, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|Magic Broadcasting sells Old School Hip-Hop simulcasts [[KDAY]]/[[Redondo Beach, California|Redondo Beach]] and [[KDEY-FM|KDEY]]/[[Ontario, California|Ontario]] (both serving the Los Angeles and Riverside/San Bernardino area) to RBC Communications for $19.5 Million. Both stations would have flipped to Chinese programming after the sale closes; however, the sale is eventually cancelled, and KDAY and KDEY keep their format.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81593/kday-los-angeles-sold/ \"KDAY Los Angeles Sold\"] from Radio-Insight (April 9, 2013)</ref> Magic once again sells the combo on December 11, this time to Merulo Media, who announce that they will retain the format despite being the owners of Spanish television outlet [[KWHY-TV]]<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86934/kday-sold-again/ KDAY SOLD AGAIN] from Radio Insight (December 11, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''10'''\n|[[CING-FM]]/[[Hamilton, Ontario]] flips from classic hits to hot adult contemporary, rebranding as \"95.3 Fresh FM.\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''11'''\n|[[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] purchases the radio and television assets of [[Fisher Communications]] for $373.3 million. The acquisition includes 20 television stations in eight markets (including [[KOMO-TV]]/[[Seattle]] and [[KATU]]/[[Portland, Oregon]]) and three radio stations in the Seattle [[media market|market]], [[KVI (AM)|KVI]], [[KOMO (AM)|KOMO-AM]] and [[KPLZ-FM|KPLZ]]. The purchase also brings Sinclair back to radio ownership for the first time since 2000, when it sold its remaining properties to [[Entercom]] and [[Emmis Communications]] (the latter buying Sinclair's St. Louis cluster).<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/66798/official-sinclair-buys-fisher-for-3733m Official: Sinclair Buys Fisher For $373.3M], ''TVNewsCheck'', April 11, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|The Top 40/CHR simulcasts of [[WHBQ-FM|WHBQ]] and [[WIVG]]/[[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] splits up as WIVG flips to Alternative as 96X, bringing the format back to the market for the first time since 2009.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81598/alternative-returns-to-memphis/ \"96X Returns To Memphis\"] from Radio Insight (April 11, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15'''\n|At approximately 2:50 PM ([[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]), [[Boston Marathon bombings|two explosions]] around [[Copley Square]], just before the photo bridge that marks the finish line, occurred during the [[2013 Boston Marathon]], about three hours after the winners crossed the line. The breaking news causes local radio stations in the Boston media market to cancel or alter regular programming to carry continuing coverage of the tragedy and allowing airstaffers to help listeners who were affected by the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/15/us/boston-marathon-explosions/index.html|title=Explosions rock Boston Marathon, several injured|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 15, 2013|date=April 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Golen |first=Jimmy |title=Two explosions at Boston marathon finish line |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/two-explosions-boston-marathon-finish-line-0 |accessdate=15 April 2013 |newspaper=AP Newswire |date=15 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415231647/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/two-explosions-boston-marathon-finish-line-0 |archivedate=15 April 2013 }}</ref> At least 3 deaths were reported, in addition to 183 people injured or wounded.<ref name=USAToday>{{cite news|title=Deaths, injuries reported after Boston Marathon blasts|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/04/15/explosions-finish-line-boston-marathon/2085193/|accessdate=15 April 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=15 April 2013}}</ref> Four days later, all Boston radio outlets (including the music outlets) preempt programming for nonstop coverage of the massive manhunt for the suspects, a pair of brothers, after a police chase and standoff that left a [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] campus police officer and one of the two suspects dead from gunshots and other suspect escaping into a neighborhood, eluding capture for most of the day until finally being arrested.<ref>[http://artery.wbur.org/2013/04/19/tv-manhunt TV Coverage Of Manhunt: Unprecedented, But Just Like It Used To Be] WBUR-FM, April 19, 2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''26'''\n|[[WMNP|WJZS]], licensed to [[Block Island, Rhode Island]] but serving the [[Newport, Rhode Island]] area 25 miles to the northeast,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mixx993.com/contact-us/contact-info|title=Contact Mixx 99.3|first=Envisionwise Website Service /|last=LinkedUpRadio|website=mixx993.com}}</ref> flips from hot AC to Tor 40/CHR as \"Mixx 99.3\" and takes the call letters WMNP.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/117851/new-look-and-sound-for-wmnp-as-mixx-99-3 \"New Look And Sound For WMNP As 'Mixx 99.3\"] from All Access (April 29, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[WOKV-FM|WFYV-FM]]/[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] ends its 33-year run as an Active Rock outlet and begins stunting, landing on a simulcast of News/Talk sister [[WOKV]] on April 30.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81612/rock-104-5-jacksonville-to-retire-april-28/ \"Rock 104.5 Jacksonville Retires; Begins Stunting\"] from All Access (April 28, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===May===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|KANR/[[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] flips from Regional Mexican to AC as \"Light 99.7\" and takes the call letters [[KHLT-FM]]. The move puts them in competition with [[KRBB]], whose former morning host (and 22-year veteran of the station) Brett Harris was just hired by KHLT as their new morning host.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81521/wichitas-fiesta-to-give-way-to-ac/ \"Wichita\u2019s Fiesta Turns On The Lite\"] from Radio Insight (May 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|103.7 [[KVIL]]/[[Dallas]]-[[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] jettisons its \"Lite FM\" moniker and returns to its call letters as its on-air identity. The station also shifts its [[adult contemporary]] playlist to include songs from the 1990s to present day.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81884/kvil-dallas-turns-out-the-lite/ \"KVIL Dallas Turns Out The Lite\"] from Radio Insight (May 2, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=5|'''6'''\n|[[Community Broadcasters, LLC]] announces it will purchase the New York-based assets of [[Backyard Broadcasting]], including market leader [[WPIG]] in [[Olean, New York|Olean]] and five stations in the Elmira-Corning market.<ref>[http://www.newzjunky.com/news/0506comm_broad.htm Community Broadcasters Announces Acquisition of Radio Stations Spanning Two Markets in Upstate New York] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130616002954/http://www.newzjunky.com/news/0506comm_broad.htm |date=2013-06-16 }}. ''Press release''. Retrieved May 6, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|The [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California]] upholds an arbitration ruling allowing ''[[The Savage Nation]]'' to leave [[Talk Radio Network]]; the [[Michael Savage]]-hosted show has been with [[Cumulus Media Networks]] since the arbitration ruling was issued in September 2012.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n|-\n|The [[KWNZ]] call letters returned to [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]], this time as a Rhythmic AC at 106.3.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81918/kwnz-reno-to-launch-monday/ \"106.3 Pop-FM Reno Debuts\"] from Radio Insight (May 6, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WINK-FM]]/[[Fort Myers, Florida]] shifts from Adult Top 40 to AC and takes the branding \"More FM.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81933/wink-fm-fort-myers-becomes-more-fm/ \"WINK-FM Fort Myers Becomes More-FM\"] from Radio Insight (May 6, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Newcap Radio|Newcap]]'s 95.9 Sun FM [[CHHI-FM]] in [[Miramichi, New Brunswick|Miramichi]] makes its debut with a hot AC format bringing the AC format back to the area when [[CFAN-FM]] flipped to country in September 2012\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|A pair of [[Dublin, Georgia]] radio stations, Classic Rock/Sports Talk hybrid [[WDBN]] (at 107.9) and R&B/Hip-Hop [[WMLT|WMLT & W245BT]] (at 1330 & 96.9), swap formats and frequencies.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81942/dublin-ga-format-swap/ \"Dublin, GA Format Swap\"] from Radio Insight (May 7, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''8'''\n|[[Sirius XM Radio]] revamps its lineup that will see the addition of new radio channels featuring programming from [[Comedy Central]] and [[Entertainment Weekly]], along with expanding [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] programming to XM channels.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81907/siriusxm-sets-channel-revamp/ \"SiriusXM Sets Lineup Revamp\"] from Radio Insight (May 4, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''13'''\n|WKZO-FM/[[Kalamazoo, Michigan]] drops its News/Talk simulcast of its [[WKZO (AM)|AM sister station]] for Alternative as \"Z96.5\" adopting the new call sign [[WZOX]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/82023/alternative-on-way-to-kalamazoo/ \"Z96.5 Brings Alternative To Kalamazoo\"] from Radio Insight (May 13, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15'''\n|Long Island, New York-based JVC Media acquires five stations in the [[Gainesville, Florida]] market with the purchase of Adult Top 40 [[WMFQ]], Talk [[WGMW|WBXY]], Smooth Jazz/AC [[WXJZ]], Country [[WXUS|WTRS]], and Sports Talk [[WYGC]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/82039/jvc-broadcasting-acquires-gainesvilleocala-cluster/ \"JVC Media Acquires Gainesville/Ocala Cluster\"] from Radio Insight (May 15, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''16'''\n|[[Bell Media]] and [[Astral Media]] sells three stations, Rhythmic Top 40 [[CKCE-FM|CKCE]]/[[Calgary]] (from Bell), and [[Winnipeg, Manitoba|Winnipeg]]'s Classic Hits [[CHIQ-FM|CHIQ]] (from Bell) and Country [[CFQX-FM|CFQX]] (from Astral), to [[Jim Pattison Group]] as part of their planned merger.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/82050/pattison-acquires-winnipeg-and-calgary-stations/ \"Pattison Acquires Winnipeg and Calgary Stations\"] from Radio Insight (May 16, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WCGH|WBYB]] (FM 103.9) moves from its original home of [[Kane, Pennsylvania]] to [[Eldred, Pennsylvania]] (in the opposite corner of [[McKean County, Pennsylvania|McKean County]]), moving into the suburbs of [[Olean, New York]] where owner [[Colonial Radio Group]] maintains most of its stations. Coinciding with the move, the station ends its simulcast of [[WAGL (FM)|WVTT]] (which also had its newsroom closed three weeks prior) and returns to [[country music]], the format it held from 1981 to 2009.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''17'''\n|After nearly 11 months with a bilingual Top 40/CHR presentation as \"Radio H20\", [[KESS-FM|KESS]]/[[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]-[[Fort Worth, Texas|Ft. Worth]] shifts to Rhythmic Top 40 as \"Hot 107.9.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/82020/h2o-dallas-to-get-hot/ \"H2O Dallas Becomes Hot 107.9\"] from Radio Insight (May 17, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''20'''\n|In what can be described as an economic and financial move, Saga Communications announces plans to limit the worldwide streaming broadcasts of their stations to the radio markets where Saga owns the outlets with a few exceptions.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/blogs/82103/no-longer-streaming-worldwide/ \"No Longer Streaming Worldwide\"] from Radio Insight (May 20, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''21'''\n|After four months off the air due to a contract dispute with [[Cumulus Media]], regionally syndicated Alabama sports talk host [[Paul Finebaum]] joins [[ESPN Inc.]] in a multimedia deal that will see Finebaum move to North Carolina.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''22'''\n|After 3 weeks of simulcasting, Cox flips the 106.5 signal, the former home of WOKV-FM (now at 104.5), to Urban AC and revives the call letters of [[WXXJ (FM)|WHJX]], which once resided at their new main competitor, [[WSOL-FM]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81891/whats-next-for-106-5-jacksonville/ \"What\u2019s Next For 106.5 Jacksonville?\"] from Radio Insight (May 19, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''23'''\n|[[WNTR]]/[[Indianapolis, Indiana|Indianapolis]] drops Adult Hits for Adult Top 40 as \"Mix 107.9.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/82086/my-indianapolis-mix-up/ \"107.9 The Mix Indianapolis Launches\"] from Radio Insight (May 23, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Just two weeks after its Country format moved to [[WCYQ]],<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/80128/journal-acquires-wnox/ \"Journal Acquires WNOX; Format Moves\"] from Radio Insight (May 9, 2013)</ref> Journal Communications flipped [[WNOX (FM)|WNOX]]/[[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] to Classic Hits.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines