is]] splits up as WIVG flips to Alternative as 96X, bringing the format back to the market for the first time since 2009.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81598/alternative-returns-to-memphis/ \"96X Returns To Memphis\"] from Radio Insight (April 11, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15'''\n|At approximately 2:50 PM ([[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]), [[Boston Marathon bombings|two explosions]] around [[Copley Square]], just before the photo bridge that marks the finish line, occurred during the [[2013 Boston Marathon]], about three hours after the winners crossed the line. The breaking news causes local radio stations in the Boston media market to cancel or alter regular programming to carry continuing coverage of the tragedy and allowing airstaffers to help listeners who were affected by the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/15/us/boston-marathon-explosions/index.html|title=Explosions rock Boston Marathon, several injured|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 15, 2013|date=April 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Golen |first=Jimmy |title=Two explosions at Boston marathon finish line |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/two-explosions-boston-marathon-finish-line-0 |accessdate=15 April 2013 |newspaper=AP Newswire |date=15 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415231647/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/two-explosions-boston-marathon-finish-line-0 |archivedate=15 April 2013 }}</ref> At least 3 deaths were reported, in addition to 183 people injured or wounded.<ref name=USAToday>{{cite news|title=Deaths, injuries reported after Boston Marathon blasts|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/04/15/explosions-finish-line-boston-marathon/2085193/|accessdate=15 April 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=15 April 2013}}</ref> Four days later, all Boston radio outlets (including the music outlets) preempt programming for nonstop coverage of the massive manhunt for the suspects, a pair of brothers, after a police chase and standoff that left a [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] campus police officer and one of the two suspects dead from gunshots and other suspect escaping into a neighborhood, eluding capture for most of the day until finally being arrested.<ref>[http://artery.wbur.org/2013/04/19/tv-manhunt TV Coverage Of Manhunt: Unprecedented, But Just Like It Used To Be] WBUR-FM, April 19, 2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''26'''\n|[[WMNP|WJZS]], licensed to [[Block Island, Rhode Island]] but serving the [[Newport, Rhode Island]] area 25 miles to the northeast,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mixx993.com/contact-us/contact-info|title=Contact Mixx 99.3|first=Envisionwise Website Service /|last=LinkedUpRadio|website=mixx993.com}}</ref> flips from hot AC to Tor 40/CHR as \"Mixx 99.3\" and takes the call letters WMNP.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/117851/new-look-and-sound-for-wmnp-as-mixx-99-3 \"New Look And Sound For WMNP As 'Mixx 99.3\"] from All Access (April 29, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[WOKV-FM|WFYV-FM]]/[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] ends its 33-year run as an Active Rock outlet and begins stunting, landing on a simulcast of News/Talk sister [[WOKV]] on April 30.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81612/rock-104-5-jacksonville-to-retire-april-28/ \"Rock 104.5 Jacksonville Retires; Begins Stunting\"] from All Access (April 28, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===May===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|KANR/[[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] flips from Regional Mexican to AC as \"Light 99.7\" and takes the call letters [[KHLT-FM]]. The move puts them in competition with [[KRBB]], whose former morning host (and 22-year veteran of the station) Brett Harris was just hired by KHLT as their new morning host.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81521/wichitas-fiesta-to-give-way-to-ac/ \"Wichita\u2019s Fiesta Turns On 