ite with Blair Garner|After Midnite]]'' on July 31.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84213/blair-garner-to-leave-after-midnite/ \"Blair Garner To Leave After Midnite,\"] from Radio Insight, 7/11/2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''24'''\n|Up 93.1 [[CIHI-FM]] makes its debut in [[Fredericton, New Brunswick|Fredericton]] reportedly with an adult hits format this comes after sister station [[CFRK-FM]] dropped classic hits for CHR in March\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''25'''\n|''[[The Phil Hendrie Show]]'' joins [[Dial Global]] after seeing its 4-year run on [[Talk Radio Network]] end.<ref>[http://rbr.com/trn-pulling-the-phil-hendrie-show/ TRN pulling the Phil Hendrie Show]. ''Radio and Television Business Report''. Retrieved June 17, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|One month before his previously announced departure from the station was to have taken place, [[Dave Rutherford]] is dropped from [[CHQR]]/[[Calgary, Alberta]] after his on-air criticism of the [[Corus Entertainment]] station's reliance on news feeds from an [[Edmonton]] [[CHED (AM)|sister station]] during the [[2013 Alberta floods|catastrophic flooding]] that affected Calgary and southern [[Alberta]].<ref>[https://nationalpost.com/m/wp/news/canada/blog.html?b=news.nationalpost.com/2013/06/26/albertas-king-of-talk-radio-dave-rutherford-fired-after-criticizing-station-over-flood-coverage \"Alberta\u2019s king of talk radio, Dave Rutherford, fired after criticizing station over flood coverage,\"] from ''National Post'', 6/26/2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[WPYA|WZNN]]/[[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] drops its sports talk format and begins stunting, first with Hawaiian music, then with patriotic music (July 4), and then to variety hits (as \"Y'all 97.3\") on July 5.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/83962/97-3-birmingham-reaches-its-end-zone/ \"What's The Deal With 97.3 Birmingham?\"] from RadioInsight, originally reported 6/25/2013, with last update 7/5/2013</ref>\n|}\n\n===July===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''1'''\n|[[WIOU (AM)|WIOU]]/[[Kokomo, Indiana]] shifts from a [[Talk radio|news/talk]]/[[Sports radio|sports]] station to a full-time sports format, largely provided by [[ESPN Radio]]. With the change, the station's existing sports programming will continue, but all political talk programming will be removed from the schedule.<ref name=kt-wiouespn>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Scott|title=WIOU switches to ESPN format|url=http://kokomotribune.com/local/x2113333801/WIOU-switches-to-ESPN-format|accessdate=June 23, 2013|newspaper=[[Kokomo Tribune]]|date=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[KXOJ-FM|KTSO]]/[[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] flips from Classic Hits to AC as 94.1 The Breeze, the first AC-formatted station in Tulsa since 2010, when [[KBEZ]] flipped to Variety Hits.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84043/breeze-blows-into-tulsa/ \"Breeze Blows Into Tulsa\"] from Radio Insight (July 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Adam Bomb replaces [[Perez Hilton]] as the host of [[Cumulus Media]]'s ''Nights Live'' program. Hilton will continue to offer gossip updates on the show.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/119900/cumulus-media-networks-to-offer-nights-live-with-a \"Cumulus Media Networks To Offer 'Nights Live With Adam Bomb'\"] from All Access (July 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=6|'''3'''\n|[[WYDB|WLQT]]/[[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]] drops AC for Country, branding themselves as \"Hot Country B94.5.\" This will be Clear Channel's second attempt with this format in this market, as the last one was tried at sister station [[WOLT (FM)|WDSJ]], which lasted only 11 months before their flip to Classic Hits in 2011.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84112/lites-off-country-on-for-dayton/ \"Lites Off; Country On For Dayton\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Billings, Montana|Billings]] picks up a second Top 40/CHR, as Classic Hits [[KKBR]] becomes \"Pop Crush 97.1.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/84012/santas-prelude-to-a-billings-kiss/ \"Billings\u2019 Pop Crush 97.1 Debuts\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Five more Cumulus-owned Country outlets are rebranded to the \"Nash FM\" brand: [[WSJR]]/Scranton-Wilkes Barre, [[WQPD|WHLZ]]/Florence, South Carolina, [[WHKR]]/Melbourne, Florida, [[KAYD-FM|KAYD]]/Beaumount, Texas, and [[WKOS]]/Kingsport, Tennessee.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84100/cumulus-nashfm-expansion-continues/ \"Cumulus\u2019 NashFM Expansion Continues\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Cumulus Media also spins off a station, as Sports Talk [[KTDK]]/Dallas is sold to Whitley Media in a unique two-part deal in which Cumulus will receive $100 in the first part of the deal. Whitley will then turn around and resell the station at which point Cumulus will receive all proceeds from that sale minus all expenses incurred in the operation of the station and from marketing and reselling the station.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84092/cumulus-sells-dfw-rimshot/ \"Cumulus Sells DFW Rimshot\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2013)</ref> However, that deal is rejected by the FCC, resulting in Cumulus taking KTDK off the air on October 6 and plans to return the license back to the FCC and moving its sports format to [[KTCK-FM|WBAP-FM]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/85346/ktck-to-replace-wbap-on-96-7-dallas/ KTCK To Replace WBAP On 96.7 Dallas] from Radio Insight (October 7, 2013)</ref> \n|-\n|The number of Adult Top 40s in Salt Lake City increases to three as AC [[KBEE]] becomes the latest entry in this battle.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84131/b98-7-salt-lake-city-shifts-to-adult-chr/ \"B98.7 Salt Lake City Shifts To Adult CHR\"] from Radio Insight (July 3, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Rogers rebrands all country stations to its unified \"Country\" branding.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''7'''\n|[[iHeartRadio]] expands its device platform to 8 countries, including its first Canadian outlets [[CHUM-FM]]/Toronto and [[CFBT-FM|CFBT]]/Vancouver, and selected stations owned by Groupo ACIR and Multimedios in Mexico.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84167/iheartradio-launches-international-suite/ \"IHeartRadio Launches International Suite\"] from Radio Insight (July 8, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''15'''\n|[[WTCB]]/[[Columbia, South Carolina]] is the latest Cumulus Media outlet to make a shift from AC to Adult Top 40.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84237/wtcb-columbia-freshens-up/ \"WTCB Columbia Freshens Up\"] from Radio Insight (July 15, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|L&L Broadcasting acquires YMF Media's [[Jackson, Mississippi]] radio cluster, which consists of Gospel [[WOAD (AM)|WOAD]], Oldies [[WJQS]], News/Talk [[WJNT]], R&B/Hip-Hop [[WJMI]], Sports [[WRKS]] and Adult R&B [[WKXI-FM|WKXI]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84244/ll-acquires-jackson-cluster/ \"L&L Acquires Jackson Cluster\"] from Radio Insight (July 15, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''16'''\n|Sandusky Publishing ends 36 years of radio ownership by selling its properties in Seattle and Phoenix to [[Hubbard Broadcasting]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/120346/hubbard-radio-acquires-10-stations-from-sandusky Hubbard Acquires 10 Stations From Sandusky] from All Access (July 16, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''18'''\n|After a year as a News/Talk simulcast, [[WMNI]]/[[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] breaks from its [[WJKR|FM simulcast]] and returns to Adult Standards.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84196/wmni-amfm-columbus-to-break-simulcast/ \"WMNI AM/FM Columbus To Break Simulcast\"] from Radio Insight (July 9, 2013)</ref> Six days later on July 24, WMNI-FM also ditched the News/Talk format and brings the [[Jack FM]] format back to Columbus.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84317/jack-returns-to-columbus/ \"Jack Returns To Columbus\"] from Radio Insight (July 24, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''24'''\n|[[KJFA (AM)|KARS]] in [[Belen, New Mexico]] completes an upgrade moving from 860 to 840&nbsp;kHz closer to Albuquerque at increased daytime power and signing on a 99 watt FM translator K275AO 102.9 launching a new modern rock format branded as \"Area 102-9\" at noon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/84222/new-area-launching-in-albuquerque/|title=Area 102.9 Albuquerque Debuts|date=July 24, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''26'''\n|[[KBZD]]/[[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] flips from Classic Country to Adult Top 40 as \"Fun 99.7.\" The flip came after two weeks of micro-stunting with a female-oriented presentation.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84349/99-7-amarillo-is-fun/ \"99.7 Amarillo Is Fun\"] from Radio Insight (July 26, 2013)</ref> The station's former manager left a message on its former [[Facebook]] page for the previous format, stating that \"They didn't like me or the format so we are both gone.\"<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/Legends997/info Legends 99.7]'s [[Facebook]] page</ref>\n|-\n|[[KMVK]]/Ft. Worth-Dallas shifts from Spanish Contemporary to Regional Mexican as \"La Grande 107.5.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84343/cbs-flips-mega-107-5-dallas/ \"CBS Flips Mega 107.5 Dallas\"] from Radio Insight (July 26, 2013)</ref> The flip would result in [[Univision]] shuffling its Dallas/Ft. Worth cluster on July 29, with KFZO becoming a simulcast of KDXX and [[KESS-FM|KESS]] dropping Rhythmic Top 40 for Regional Mexican.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84403/univision-shuffles-dallas-signals/ \"Univision Shuffles Dallas Signals\"] from Radio Insight (July 29, 2013)</ref> KESS's \"Hot\" format was relocated to its HD2 subchannel where it remained until mid-August.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[KNRQ]]/[[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]] officially switches signals from 97.9 to 103.7, replacing [[KXPC-FM|KXPC]], which [[Cumulus Media]] acquired in a swap with EMF for KRUZ/Santa Barbara in 2011. Cumulus has taken over the KXPC calls and parked them at the 97.9 frequency, which relocated to [[Aloha, Oregon]] and began targeting the [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] area, where it expedited construction on a new transmitter and start testing with music until a new format is launched.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84329/knrq-eugene-to-make-move-to-103-7/ \"KNRQ Eugene Moves To 103.7\"] from Radio Insight (July 28, 2013)</ref> On August 5, EMF purchases KXPC from Cumulus, who will turn the station into a K-Love network affiliate, replacing co-owned rimshot [[KLVP]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84517/emf-acquires-cumulus-portland-move-in/ \"EMF Acquires Cumulus\u2019 Portland Move-In\"] from Radio Insight (August 5, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''30'''\n|After seven months with a Sports Talk format, [[WOSL|WCFN]]/[[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]] returns to Rhythmic Oldies for the third time as \"Old School 100.3.\" They become the first station in the US to drop its affiliation with [[CBS Sports Radio]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/84440/wcfn-cincinnati-goes-old-school/ \"WCFN Cincinnati Goes Old School\"] from Radio Insight (July 30, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''31'''\n|[[KDMR|KPHN]]/[[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] and [[KDIS-FM]]/[[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] ([[Radio Disney]] [[Owned-and-operated station]]s with sale pending), went [[Dark (broadcasting)|Silent]].<ref name=v-2013selloff/><ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/82260/radio-disney-places-stations-on-the-market/ Radio Disney Places Stations On The Market] from Radio Insight (August 11, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===August===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|[[WLPA (AM)|WLPA]]/[[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]] switches from [[Fox Sports Radio]] (which it had carried since July 2005) to [[ESPN Radio]]. The station had attempted to affiliate with ESPN Radio for some years beforehand, but was unable to do so due to its geographic proximity to [[WGLD]]/[[Manchester Township, York County, Pennsylvania|Manchester Township]]; however, WGLD's owner, [[Cumulus Media]], affiliated its sports stations with [[CBS Sports Radio]] in early 2013, making the ESPN affiliation available to WLPA.<ref name=sn-wlpaespn>{{cite news|last=Stark|first=Eric|title=WLPA drops FOX in favor of ESPN|url=http://lancasteronline.com/article/local/864034_WLPA-drops-FOX-in-favor-of-ESPN.html|accessdate=July 16, 2013|newspaper=[[Sunday News (Lancaster)|Sunday News]]|date=June 23, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130717084326/http://lancasteronline.com/article/local/864034_WLPA-drops-FOX-in-favor-of-ESPN.html|archive-date=2013-07-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|Clear Channel sells its stake in [[Sirius XM Radio]] and will remove its programming from the lineup effective August 28, leaving only [[KIIS-FM]]/Los Angeles and [[WHTZ]]/New York City as the only terrestrial offering on Sirius XM's channel lineup.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84485/clear-channel-sells-siriusxm-stake-stations-to-leave-service/ \"Clear Channel Sells SiriusXM Stake; Stations To Leave Service\"] from Radio Insight (August 2, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|[[Boston University]] sells [[WBUR]]'s 1240 AM in [[West Yarmouth, Massachusetts]] (on [[Cape Cod]]) to Alex Langer, who will program it with [[Portuguese-language]] programming similar to that of new sister station [[WSRO]]/[[Ashland, Massachusetts|Ashland]]. The 1240 AM facility had been deemed redundant following the acquisition of [[WBUA]]/[[Tisbury, Massachusetts|Tisbury]] in February.<ref name=tbg-wburamsale>{{cite news|last=Reidy|first=Chris|title=Langer Broadcasting to buy 1240 AM signal in West Yarmouth from WBUR|url=http://www.boston.com/businessupdates/2013/08/05/langer-broadcasting-buy-signal-west-yarmouth-from-wbur/Xn88j1ERRbBiFlDJNXSECI/story.html|accessdate=August 6, 2013|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|Merlin Media reaches a deal to sell [[WKVP|WWIQ]]/[[Philadelphia]] to the [[Educational Media Foundation]]. With the sale, the station will end its year-old news/talk format and return to religious programming (it had been a [[Family Radio]] station from 1968 until 2012); this move will leave ''[[Imus in the Morning]]'', ''[[Glenn Beck Program|The Glenn Beck Program]]'' and ''[[The Sean Hannity Show]]'' uncleared in the Philadelphia market.<ref name=pdn-wwiqemf>{{cite news|last=Takiff|first=Jonathan|title=Rush, Hannity & Beck Could Lose Philly Pulpit|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/gizmo/218755212.html|accessdate=August 8, 2013|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|date=August 7, 2013}}</ref><ref name=aa-wwiqemf>{{cite news|title=Confirmed: Merlin Sells IQ 106.9/Philadelphia To EMF|url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/121083/confirmed-merlin-sells-iq-106-9-philadelphia-to-em|accessdate=August 8, 2013|newspaper=All Access|date=August 8, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]'' is likely to return to former affiliate [[WPHT]].<ref>[http://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/molly_eichel/20131010_Rush_Limbaugh_to_return_to_WPHT.html Rush Limbaugh could return to WPHT]. ''philly.com''. Retrieved October 10, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''8'''\n|[[Rick Jeanneret]], the radio (and later television) play-by-play voice of the [[Buffalo Sabres]] since 1971, announces his retirement effective in 2016 and that he will reduce his duties each season until that time. [[Dan Dunleavy]], previously the play-by-play man for the rival [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], will move across the border and serve as Jeanneret's substitute, taking over fully for Jeanneret in 2016 (whether Dunleavy's duties will include both radio and TV is not yet known; the Sabres' television contract expires in 2016).\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''12'''\n|[[WMGC-FM|WMGC]]/[[Detroit]] drops AC for Sports and becomes the new affiliate for [[ESPN Radio]], as well as featuring local content. They will face competition from [[WXYT-FM|WXYT]], who currently dominates the ratings and has broadcast rights to the four sports teams in Detroit.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/121191/it-s-official-wmgc-detroit-flips-to-sports \"It's Official: WMGC/Detroit Flips To Sports\"] from All Access (August 12, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[KARW|KYZZ]]/Salinas-Monterey, which previously carried ESPN Radio until it left the air on May 24, returns to the air with a Classical format, filling the void that was left by [[KDFG|KBOQ]] in 2011.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/82172/buckley-sells-kyzz-to-mount-wilson/ \"KYZZ Returns As K-Mozart\"] from Radio Insight (August 12, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14'''\n|After a 26-year run as a Classic Rock station, [[KRXO-FM|KRXO]]/[[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]] began transitioning from its long time home at 107.7 to its translator at 104.5 and KRXO's HD2 channel. The 107.7 signal flips to Sports Talk, putting it in competition with [[WWLS-FM]] and is expected to lure the airstaffers over from that station to help launch the upstart.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84202/rumor-mill-krxo-oklahoma-city-to-flip-to-sports/ \"KRXO Oklahoma City To Flip To Sports; Classic Rock Moving\"] from Radio Insight (July 10, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''15'''\n|Two MBS radio stations in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], [[New Brunswick|NB]] flipped formats: [[CJYC-FM]] flipped to [[classic hits]] as \"Kool 98\", while [[CFBC]] flips from oldies/classic hits to country.\n|-\n|[[CKDH-FM]] in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia]] flips from AC/hot AC to country.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''16'''\n|[[KHTB|KENZ]]/Salt Lake City drops Alternative for Classic Hits, giving the market its fourth outlet with the same format.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/83906/cumulus-planning-major-salt-lake-shuffle/ \"KENZ Begins Salt Lake Shuffle As Classic Hits 101.9\"] from Radio Insight (August 16, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[KNOB (FM)|KNOB]]/[[Santa Rosa, California]] drops the [[Bob FM]] format for Alternative after declining ratings. The station's logo is loosely patterned after sister station [[WROX-FM|WROX]]/[[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]]<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84661/knob-turns-its-bob-to-alternative/ \"KNOB Turns Its Bob To Alternative\"] from Radio Insight (August 17, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''17'''\n|[[KWDZ]]/[[Salt Lake City]] ([[Radio Disney]] [[Owned-and-operated station|O&O station]]) dropped the affiliation and went [[Dark (broadcasting)|Silent]].<ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101568930&formid=910&fac_num=2445 Notification of Suspension of Operations KWDZ] - United States [[Federal Communications Commission]]</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''18'''\n|Just one year after it was sold to [[Lincoln Financial Media]], ESPN Radio affiliate [[WSFS (FM)|WAXY-FM]]/[[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]] officially completes its move into [[Miramar, Florida|Miramar]], giving the station full signal coverage into the Miami-Ft. Lauderdale market,<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84668/waxy-fm-completes-miami-move-in/ \"WAXY-FM Completes Miami Move-In\"] from Radio Insight (August 18, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=3|'''19'''\n|[[KXSN|KIFM]]/[[San Diego, California|San Diego]] shifts from Smooth AC to Soft AC as \"Easy 98.1.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84701/kifm-san-diego-goes-easy/ KIFM San Diego Goes Easy] from Radio Insight (August 19, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|After a day of stunting with a \"Wheel of Formats\", Active Rock [[KQWB-FM]]/[[Fargo, North Dakota]] flips to Adult Top 40 as \"Big 98.7\"<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/121483/fargo-gets-big \"Fago Gets Big\"] from All Access (August 20, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|After 23 years as an Adult Top 40, [[WLVW|WRQX]]/[[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] adjusts its direction and returns to Top 40/CHR. It also dropped the \"Mix 107.3\" moniker in favor of \"All The Hits.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/84727/wrqx-ditching-its-mix-moniker-for-all-the-hits/ \"WRQX Ditching Its Mix Moniker For All The Hits\"] from Radio Insight (August 19, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''26'''\n|[[Bell Media]] spins off five stations, [[CFXJ-FM|CFXJ]] & [[CHBM-FM|CHBM]]/Toronto, and [[CISL (AM)|CISL]], [[CKZZ-FM|CKZZ]] & [[CHHR-FM|CHHR]]/Vancouver, to [[Newcap Radio]] for (CDN)$112 Million.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84781/newcap-acquires-toronto-and-vancouver-stations/ \"Newcap Acquires Toronto And Vancouver Stations\"] from Radio Insight (August 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[CKUL-FM]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] flips from classic hits to adult alternative/triple A branded as \"Radio 96.5\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''29'''\n|[[Rogers Media]] rebrands all four EZ rock stations to the ''Kiss FM'' branding\n|-\n|[[CJRW-FM]] [[Summerside, Prince Edward Island]] flips from classic rock (102.1 Spud FM) to hot AC (Spud 102 FM) becoming the fourth MBS radio station to change formats\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=5|'''30'''\n|After stunting with news of an \"Alien Invasion\" that resulted in local law enforcement adding security measures to area schools, [[WMSR-FM|WMSR]]/[[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]] flips from Top 40/CHR to AAA<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84837/format-change-stunt-in-muscle-shoals-leads-to-extra-school-security/ \"Format Change Stunt In Muscle Shoals Leads To Extra School Security And AAA\"] from Radio Insight (August 30, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|After 22 years of AAA, [[KHTP|KMTT]]/[[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]]-[[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] flips to Rhythmic Hot AC as \"Hot 103.7, The Rhythm of Seattle.\" The flip fills the void left by [[KQMV]], who shifted to Top 40/CHR in 2011.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84872/entercom-flips-seattles-mountain-to-hot-103-7/ \"Entercom Flips Seattle\u2019s Mountain To Hot 103.7\"] from Radio Insight (August 30, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|In a unique but complex deal, Cumulus Media acquires [[Dial Global]] for $260 Million, plus an additional $45 Million as part of a retiring debt deal. Cumulus will then merge its in-house and Dial Global's network and syndication operations into a newly revived version of [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]]. Cumulus then in turn sell 53 stations to [[Townsquare Media]] and 15 more to Peak Broadcasting, the latter swapping its [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] cluster to Cumulus as part of the arrangement.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84851/are-these-the-markets-in-the-cumulustownsquaredial-global-deal/ \"Cumulus Makes Dial Global And Townsquare Deals Official\"] from Radio Insight (August 30, 2013)</ref> Cumulus also buys back the [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]] cluster it had LMA'd to Clear Channel in 2009.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84861/cumulus-to-reacquire-green-bay-stations-from-clear-channel/ \"Cumulus To Reacquire Green Bay Stations From Clear Channel\"] from Radio Insight (August 30, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[CKX-FM]]/[[Brandon, Manitoba|Brandon]] abruptly flips from mainstream rock to variety hits, branded as \"Bob FM.\"\n|-\n|Classic rocker [[CHNS-FM]]/[[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] flips to classic hits as \"The Wave.\" This quickly fills a void left in the Halifax market after [[Newcap Radio|Newcap]]'s [[CKUL-FM]] flipped to AAA.\n|-\n|}\n\n===September===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|Cumulus Media makes its third format change in their Salt Lake City radio cluster, as it flips Active Rock [[KENZ (FM)|KHTB]] to Alternative as \"ALT 94.9.\" The station will retain their airstaff and in the process shifts the Active Rock product over to sister station [[KBER]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84896/z-rock-salt-lake-city-flips-to-alt-94-9/ \"Z-Rock Salt Lake City Flips To Alt 94.9\"] from Radio Insight (September 2, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|[[WWKB]]/[[Buffalo, New York]] ends its seven-year run as a [[progressive talk radio]] outlet and adopts a 24/7 feed of [[ESPN Radio]]. WWKB takes over the ESPN affiliation from sister station [[WGR]], who had been a charter affiliate of the network since 1992. WWKB's existing sports rights and brokered weekend programs will continue unaffected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/6/liberal-talk-radio-station-goes-busts-buffalo/|title=Liberal talk radio station goes busts in Buffalo, replaced by ESPN programming|first=The Washington Times|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|website=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''6'''\n|Cumulus Media rebrands 6 more Country outlets to the \"Nash FM\" brand: [[WFYR]]/[[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]], [[WJCL-FM|WJCL]]/[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[KAMO-FM|KAMO]]/[[Fayetteville, Arkansas]], [[KXKC]]/[[Lafayette, Louisiana]], [[WMDH-FM|WMDH]]/[[Muncie, Indiana]], and [[WLFF]]/[[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina]].<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/122069/nash-fm-branding-6-more-stations Nash FM branding 6 More Stations] from All Access (September 6, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''12'''\n|[[CKMX]] [[Calgary]] ditches its [[classic country]] format as it flips to all-comedy radio as Funny 1060\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''13'''\n|Cumulus Media pulls the plug on its last \"Gen X\" formatted outlet, as [[WRQQ]]/[[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] flips to Classic Hits.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/85025/wrqq-baton-rouge-shifts-to-classic-hits/ WRQQ Baton Rouge Shifts To Classic Hits] from Radio Insight (September 13, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"  rowspan=2|'''19'''\n|[[CJED-FM]]/[[Niagara Falls, Ontario]] dumps its adult hits format and begins [[stunting (broadcasting)|stunting]] with [[Christmas music]]. All original programming ceases the next day as the station begins simulcasting [[CFLZ-FM]]/[[Fort Erie, Ontario|Fort Erie]].\n|-\n|The [[Kennewick, Washington|Kennewick]]/[[Richland, Washington|Richland]]/[[Pasco, Washington]] radio market picks a Rhythmic Top 40, as Classic Hits [[KOLW]] becomes \"Hot 97.5.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/85120/kolw-goes-from-kool-to-hot/ \"KOLW Goes From Kool To Hot\"] from Radio Insight (September 19, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''20'''\n|First Media Radio files to sell [[WCBT]]/[[Roanoke Rapids, North Carolina]] to Johnson Broadcast Ventures. Upon the sale's completion, the station will drop its [[Sports radio|sports talk]] programming from [[ESPN Radio]] for a music format featuring [[Gospel music|gospel]] and [[classic soul]].<ref name=tdh-wcbtsale>{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Della|title=WCBT 1230 AM of First Media Radio to be sold|url=http://www.rrdailyherald.com/news/wcbt-am-of-first-media-radio-to-be-sold/article_2f49533a-2897-11e3-a6ee-0019bb2963f4.html|accessdate=September 29, 2013|newspaper=[[Daily Herald (Roanoke Rapids)|The Daily Herald]]|date=September 29, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''24'''\n|[[WURV]]/[[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] shifts from Modern AC to Adult Top 40 as \"Play 103.7.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/85165/wurv-richmond-presses-play/ WURV Richmond Presses Play] from Radio Insight (September 24, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''26'''\n|[[WLKK]]/[[Wethersfield, New York]] flips to Alternative, ending its two-year simulcast of [[WBEN (AM)|WBEN]].<ref>Pergament, Alan (September 25, 2013). [http://blogs.buffalonews.com/talkintv/2013/09/my-entry-1.html Ch.2's Levin and Dudzik a comedy team; Schultz hire a bad PR move] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927065906/http://blogs.buffalonews.com/talkintv/2013/09/my-entry-1.html |date=2013-09-27 }}. ''The Buffalo News''. Retrieved September 25, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[WOPG (AM)|WDDY]]/[[Albany, New York|Albany]],<ref name='WDDY'>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101580917&formid=910&fac_num=72117 Notification of Suspension of Operations WDDY] - United States [[Federal Communications Commission]]</ref> [[WDZY]]/[[Colonial Heights, Virginia|Colonial Heights]]-[[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]],<ref name='WDZY'>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101580916&formid=910&fac_num=21723 Notification of Suspension of Operations WDZY] - United States [[Federal Communications Commission]]</ref> [[WSJP (AM)|WKSH]]/[[Sussex, Wisconsin|Sussex]]-[[Milwaukee]]<ref name='WKSH'>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101580909&formid=910&fac_num=87121 Notification of Suspension of Operations WKSH] - United States [[Federal Communications Commission]]</ref> and [[KRDY]]/[[San Antonio]]<ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101580914&formid=910&fac_num=26310 Notification of Suspension of Operations KRDY] - United States [[Federal Communications Commission]]</ref> ([[Radio Disney]] [[Owned-and-operated station]]s with sale pending), went [[Dark (broadcasting)|