nolulu County, Hawaii|Honolulu]] drops Soft AC/Adult Standards for Filipino programing under a LMA from Imelda Ortega Anderson\u2019s Pinoy Power Media and takes the new calls KPRP.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/85315/krtr-shifts-to-filipino-programming/ KRTR Shifts To Filipino Programming] from Radio Insight (October 4, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''5'''\n|In a complicated, multi-band frequency swap, brokered religious station [[WVOA-LP|WVOA]] moves its programming to the audio feed of the former WMBO (87.7, in TV channel 6), while the station's former FM frequency (103.9/[[Mexico, New York]]) changes its call sign to [[WSEN (FM)|WNDR-FM]] and begins stunting with [[Christmas music]].<ref>Herbert, Geoff (October 6, 2013). [http://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2013/10/syracuse_radio_holiday_music_christmas_holly_fm.html Syracuse radio station starts playing holiday music 11 weeks before Christmas]. ''Syracuse Post-Standard''. Retrieved October 7, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''11'''\n|Just one year after it dropped the format for Spanish AC and later to Variety Hits respectively, [[WMIB|WSHE-FM]]/[[Miami, Florida|Miami]] returns to R&B/Hip-Hop and revives its \"103.5 The Beat\" moniker.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/85371/format-change-imminent-in-miami/ \"WSHE Miami Drops A Beat Again\"] from Radio Insight (October 11, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14'''\n|[[Talk Radio Network]] sues one of its last remaining hosts, [[Jerry Doyle]]. The move comes just days after another TRN host, [[Andrea Tantaros]], had sued the network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talkers.com/2013/10/14/monday-october-14-2013/|title=Monday, October 14, 2013|date=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''21'''\n|[[KTCK-FM|WBAP-FM]]/[[Flower Mound, Texas]] switches from the simulcast of [[WBAP (AM)|WBAP News/Talk 820 AM]] to a simulcast of [[KTCK (AM)|KTCK SportsRadio 1310 The Ticket]]. The FM simulcast of WBAP-AM moves to [[KPLX|KPLX 99.5]] [[HD Radio|HD2]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.dfw.com/2013/10/07/833731/sportsradio-1310-the-ticket-to.html \u2018SportsRadio 1310 the Ticket\u2019 to also air on 96.7 FM] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013020458/http://www.dfw.com/2013/10/07/833731/sportsradio-1310-the-ticket-to.html |date=2013-10-13 }} - ''[http://www.dfw.com DFW.com]'' (released October 7, 2013, updated October 8, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''23'''\n|CKKY [[Wainwright, Alberta]] abandons the [[country music]] format and the Key 83 branding as it moves from its AM 830 position to 101.9 FM becoming K-Rock 101.9 with a [[classic rock|classic]]/[[mainstream rock]] format\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|The Santa Barbara Foundation announces that it will sell [[KDB (FM)|KDB]]/[[Santa Barbara, California]]. In a statement, the station said that it was unable to attract enough revenue from contributing listeners to support KDB's operations, despite an increase in advertising revenue. The foundation hopes to sell the station at a discount to interests that would retain KDB's [[classical music]] format (citing the \"continuing community benefit\" of continuing this programming), but will also consider full-price offers from groups that will program a format of their choosing (in which the proceeds will go toward an endowment to support classical music in the area).<ref name=sbi-kdbforsale>{{cite news|last=Hayden|first=Tyler|title=KDB 93.7 FM on the Auction Block|url=http://independent.com/news/2013/oct/28/kdb-937-fm-auction-block/|accessdate=October 28, 2013|newspaper=[[Santa Barbara Independent]]|date=October 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201415/http://independent.com/news/2013/oct/28/kdb-937-fm-auction-block/|archive-date=October 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''31'''\n|As part of a shuffle that was arraigned by the FCC in 2006, four stations will switch frequencies on this date: [[KSAS-FM|KSAS]]/[[Boise, Idaho]] will move from 103.3 to 103.5, [[KSKI-FM|KSKI]]/[[Sun Valley, Idaho]] will relocate from 103.7 to 94.5, and [[KEDJ|KZNO]]/[[Jerome, Idaho]] shifting from 102.9 to 103.1, paving the way for [[KZMG|KPHD]]/[[Elko, Nevada]], which broadcasts at 97.5, to change its COL to [[Melba, Idaho]], thus entering the Boise market and change its frequency to 102.7.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86466/ksas-changing-frequencies/ KSAS Changing Frequencies] from Radio Insight (October 27, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===November===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=4|'''1'''\n|[[WNCB|WKSL]]/[[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] flips from Rhythmic Top 40 to Country as \"B93.9.\" The station will challenge the more dominant [[WQDR-FM|WQDR]] for listeners in the Research Triangle area.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86530/b93-9-starts-country-duel-in-raleigh/ \"B93.9 Starts Country Duel In Raleigh\"] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|The \"KISS-FM\" branding returns to [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], as [[WKSL|WNWW]] ditches the \"Radio Now\" branding after 2 years.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86519/kiss-returns-in-jacksonville/ \"Kiss Returns In Jacksonville\"] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|The San Diego Top 40 radio war will lose a competitor, as Cherry Creek Radio sells rimshot [[KYDO|KSIQ]] to Educational Media Foundation, who at the same time also makes a deal that will see [[KKCS (FM)|KKCS]]/[[Colorado Springs, Colorado]] swap frequencies with [[Pueblo, Colorado|Pueblo]] Country outlet [[KLCX|KIQN]]. Both deals will close in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/86539/emf-buys-in-san-diego-swaps-in-colorado/|title=EMF Buys In San Diego & Swaps In Colorado|date=November 7, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Paducah, Kentucky]] loses a Classic Rock outlet, as [[WZYK|WQQR]] begins stunting with Christmas music that will lead up to a format flip after the holiday season.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86534/94-7-wqqr-drops-classic-rock-for-christmas/ \"http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86534/94-7-wqqr-drops-classic-rock-for-christmas/\"] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2013)</ref> WQQR also joins a growing list of stations in the United States to jump on the Christmas Music bandwagon that even saw rival outlets in Louisville and Norfolk enter the fray on this date.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86515/christmas-comes-early-across-america/ \"Christmas Comes Early Across America\"] from Radio Insight (November 1, 2013)</ref> The Classic Rock format would quickly find a new home on November 6 at former Adult Top 40 [[WJLI]].<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86604/wjli-fills-classic-rock-void-in-paducah/ \"WJLI fills Classic Rock void in Paducah\"] from Radio Insight (November 6, 2013)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''6'''\n|Non-commercial Top 40/CHR [[KVIT]]/[[Apache Junction, Arizona]], a student-run outlet serving the [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] area based out of the [[East Valley Institute of Technology]], flips to Dance and bills itself as \"Teen Pulse Radio.\" The station becomes the second student-run outlet in the United States (after [[KNHC-FM|KNHC]]/Seattle) to program a full-time Dance format.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86598/phoenixs-goldmine-gets-a-pulse/ Phoenix's Goldmine gets a pulse] from Radio Insight (November 6, 2013)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|[[Rusty Humphries]] leaves [[Talk Radio Network]] for undisclosed reasons.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''8'''\n|After three years as a Top 40/CHR, [[WEKL|WZNY]]/[[Augusta, Georgia]] picks up the Classic Rock format of sister station [[WLUB|WEKL]], who in turn flips back to Country after seven years as \"G105.7.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86625/eagle-moves-in-augusta-to-make-way-for-country/ Eagle moves in Augusta to make way for Country] from Radio Insight (November 8, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''14'''\n|In a unanimous decision that included the support of The Minority Media And Telecommunications Council, The [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]] approved loosening restrictions to allow foreign companies to expand its ownership of broadcasting properties beyond the 25% cap on a case by case basis.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86459/fcc-prepares-vote-on-foreign-ownership/ FCC Prepares Vote On Foreign Ownership] from Radio Insight (October 24, 2013)</ref><ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/124313/proposal-to-loosen-foreign-ownership-restrictions- Proposal To Loosen Foreign Ownership Restrictions Approved By FCC] from All Access (November 14, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''15'''\n|[[WRCN-FM|WRCN]]/[[Long Island, New York]] drops its Mainstream Rock format and starts playing Christmas Music in advance of launching a News/Talk format after the Holiday season.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86698/wrcn-to-flip-to-newstalk-after-christmas-music/ WRCN TO FLIP TO NEWS/TALK; AFTER CHRISTMAS MUSIC] from Radio Insight (November 15, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''18'''\n|After a nine-year run in the morning slot since its flip from Rhythmic AC to News/Talk in 2004, Jim Quinn and Rose Somma Tennent exit [[WPGB]]/[[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] and in the process end their syndicated voice tracked program \u201cThe War Room with Quinn & Rose,\u201d after the hosts and station management could not come to terms on a new contract.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86712/quinn-rose-exit-wpgb/ QUINN & ROSE EXIT WPGB] from Radio Insight (November 18, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''22'''\n|[[WTMJ (AM)|WTMJ]]/[[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] announces it will not renew its agreement with Learfield Communications to air [[Wisconsin Badgers]] broadcasts after the 2013-2014 academic year. WTMJ had aired Badger broadcasts in one form or another for 86 years, holding broadcast rights directly until Learfield acquired the rights in 1994.<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/233056621.html \"After 86 years, WTMJ-AM to end Wisconsin Badgers broadcasts,\"] from ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', 11/22/2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''28'''\n|[[WXDJ|WRMA]]/Miami dropped their Rhythmic Top 40 format and swapped frequencies with Tropical sister [[WRMA|WXDJ]]. The move comes in the wake of morning host DJ Laz's departure from WRMA and sister station [[KXOL-FM|KXOL]]/Los Angeles November 22, along with low ratings for WRMA since the flip from Spanish Contemporary in June 2012.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/86795/wheres-dj-laz-sbs-prepping-miami-swap/ WHERE\u2019S DJ LAZ? SBS PREPPING MIAMI SWAP?] from Radio Insight (November 26, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n===December===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''1'''\n|[[WSHE-FM|WILV]]/[[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] drops its Retro-based 80s format and makes a transition back towards a current-based AC format, which it previously had before 1997, and fills the void left by WLIT back in June.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86820/wilv-rewound-no-more/ \"WILV Rewound No More\"] from Radio Insight (December 1, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''2'''\n|The CRTC approves power increases for [[Cogeco]]'s [[Montreal]] properties, as Francophone Talk [[CHMP-FM|CHMP]] (at 40.8Kw) and Anglophone Rhythmic Top 40 [[CKBE-FM|CKBE]] (at 44.1Kw) both upgrade their power to 100&nbsp;kW respectively. Both moves are being enabled by the lifting of the Department of Industry's moratorium on power increases at the site in the heart of Montreal.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/124739/montreal-fm-pair-gets-crtc-ok-for-power-increases Montreal FM Pair Gets CRTC OK For Power Increases] from All Access (December 2, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''6'''\n|The [[Educational Media Foundation]] adds Rhythmic Top 40 [[WHVK|WHWT]]/[[Huntsville, Alabama]] to its list of acquistitions, bringing the K-Love format to the market in 2014.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86884/emf-acquires-hot-103-5-huntsville/ EMF Acquires Hot 103.5 Huntsville] from Radio Insight (December 6, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''7'''\n|[[WEMP]]/[[Two Rivers, Wisconsin]] begins broadcasting under [[program test authority]] for a one-day period with [[easy listening]] music interspersed with oldies, nine days before the station's construction permit was to expire. The station uses [[WLKN]]/[[Cleveland, Manitowoc County, Wisconsin|Cleveland]]'s studios, tower and transmitter for the PTA, with WLKN going silent for the day to allow it.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''8'''\n|Clear Channel's Australian subsididary [[Australian Radio Network]] announced that it will relaunch its [[Sydney, New South Wales|Sydney]] Adult Top 40 outlet Mix 106.5 as Top 40/CHR \"KIIS 106.5\" on January 20, 2014, with former [[2Day FM]] personalities [[Kyle & Jackie O]] taking over the morning slot. The move comes as ARN expands the [[KISS-FM (brand)|KISS-FM]] brand Down Under with relaunches being planned for its \"Mix FM\" outlets in Melbourne, Brisbane, Adelaide, and Canberra.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/86703/clear-channel-to-spread-kiis-brand-down-under/ ARN OFFICIALLY ANNOUNCES LAUNCH OF KIIS 106.5 SYDNEY] from Radio Insight (December 8, 2014)</ref> However, on December 18, a Cease & Desist was filed against ARN by narrowcaster [[Kiss FM Australia]], claiming legal use of the name since 2005 and repeated warnings on November 27 over ARN using the branding, citing trade mark infringement rights.<ref>[http://www.radioinfo.com.au/news/cease-and-desist-using-kiis-name Cease and desist using KIIS name] from RadioInfo Australia (December 18, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''9'''\n|After spending two weeks with a part-time [[Rhythmic adult contemporary|Rhythmic Hot AC]] direction on evenings and weekends, Adult Hits [[WKQX (FM)|WIQI]]/Chicago goes full-time with the format.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86907/i101-chicago-shifts-to-rhythmic-hot-ac/ I101 CHICAGO SHIFTS TO RHYTHMIC HOT AC] from Radio Insight (December 9, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''13'''\n|After six years with Adult Hits, [[WDRQ]]/[[Detroit]] flips to Country and adopts the \"Nash FM\" moniker.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/125180/wdrq-detroit-flips-to-country WDRQ/Detroit Flips To Country] from All Access (December 13, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''16'''\n|Top 40/CHR [[WXKS-FM|WXKS]]/Boston apologizes to listeners and concertgoers after lying onstage during their December 14 Jingle Ball holiday concert that headliner [[Miley Cyrus]] was at the [[TD Garden]] ready to perform, but she and her entourage was stuck at Teterboro Airport in New Jersey and unable to make her flight into Boston for the show due to a snowstorm that cancelled all flights in parts of the Northeast. While Cyrus called into night host Mikey V to tell him what happened, the other air staffers were \"teasing\" the concertgoers who were in the building that Cyrus was there, joking around about trying to get ready before going on stage for over two hours before coming clean to the audience.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86989/wxks-gets-caught-lying-to-audience/  WXKS GETS CAUGHT LYING TO AUDIENCE] from Radio Insight (December 17, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''23'''\n|Clear Channel Communications and Cumulus Media made a massive shuffle affecting primarily its conservative talk lineup. \n*''[[The Rush Limbaugh Show]]'' and ''[[The Sean Hannity Show]]'' will both end their carriage contracts with former flagship station [[WABC (AM)|WABC]]/[[New York City]] and, beginning January 2, 2014, move to crosstown rival [[WOR (AM)|WOR]], which had been acquired by Clear Channel in 2012.<ref>Byers, Dylan (May 5, 2013). [http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/05/rush-limbaugh-may-leave-cumulus-163282.html Rush Limbaugh may leave Cumulus]. ''Politico''. Retrieved May 6, 2013.</ref><ref>Hinckley, David (May 6, 2013). [http://m.nydailynews.com/1.1335773 Rush Limbaugh: Don\u2019t blame me for WABC\u2019s declining ad sales]. ''New York Daily News''. Retrieved May 6, 2013.</ref><ref>Byers, Dylan (July 28, 2013). [http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/07/cumulus-planning-to-drop-rush-limbaugh-sean-hannity-169371.html?hp=f2 Cumulus planning to drop Rush Limbaugh, Sean Hannity]. ''Politico''. Retrieved July 29, 2013.</ref>\n*In Los Angeles, Limbaugh will leave longtime West Coast flagship [[KFI]] and join Hannity as the anchors of an all-syndicated conservative talk format on [[KEIB|KTLK]].<ref name=lat126>Faughnder, Ryan (December 6, 2013). [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-rush-limbaugh-kfi-ktlk-20131204,0,3611081.story#axzz2mj6zJwRV Clear Channel moving Rush Limbaugh from KFI to revamped KTLK]. ''Los Angeles Times''. Retrieved December 6, 2013.</ref>\n*In San Francisco, Limbaugh and Hannity will leave [[KKSF (AM)|KKSF]] and move to [[KNEW (AM)|KNEW]]. Both KTLK and KNEW are Clear Channel-owned stations that had previously aired progressive talk formats, which are being abandoned in the format changes.<ref name=lat126/>\n*Cumulus Media will move ''[[The Savage Nation]]'' into Hannity's former time slot on its stations, will cancel existing programs hosted by [[Geraldo Rivera]] and [[Mike Huckabee]], and bring in [[Dennis Miller]] from [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]] (which Cumulus received in a swap with Oaktree Capital Management in August) to fill Limbaugh's former time slot. (Rivera's show will continue as a local show on WABC.)\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=6|'''26'''\n|Clear Channel makes major format and frequency adjustments in four markets:\n*In Des Moines, both Adult Top 40 [[KXNO-FM|KPTL]] and Alternative [[KCYZ|KCCQ]] swap places and relaunch with new brandings, as KCCQ becomes \"ALT 106.3\" and KPTL becomes \"NOW 105.1.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/87096/clear-channel-flips-two-in-des-moines/ Clear Channel Flips Two In Des Moines] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n*In Sacramento, KHLX, which had programmed Classic Hits until November when it began playing Christmas Music, became a simulcast of [[KFBK (AM)|KFBK]] and swapped call letters and frequency positions with [[KFBK-FM]], who took over the 93.1 position. [[KBEB|KHLX]], now at 92.5 flipped to a new format in 2014.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/87047/clear-channel-prepping-sacramento-changes/ KFBK-FM Moves To 93.1; Making Way For New 92.5 Format] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n*In [[Jackson, Mississippi]], [[WJDX-FM]] shifts from Oldies to Classic Hits as \"105.1 The River.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/87101/wjdx-flows-down-the-river/ WJDX Flows Down The River] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n*In San Diego, [[KSSX]] shifts from Rhythmic Oldies to Rhythmic Hot AC.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/125409/kssx-heats-up-rhythmic-ac-kiss-fm KSSX Heats Up Rhythmic AC \"Kiss-FM\"] from All Access (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Classic Hits [[WRND (AM)|WEGI]] & [[WRND (FM)|WEGI-FM]]/[[Clarksville, Tennessee]] flips to Variety Hits as \"Rewind 94.3.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/87068/wegi-to-rewind-itself/ WEGI To Rewind Itself] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[CHFM]]/[[Calgary]] drops Adult Contemporary for Adult Top 40 as \"95.9 Kiss FM\", giving that market three Top 40 stations.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/84520/lites-going-off-in-calgary/ Calgary's Lite Becomes Kiss] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|[[WPHR-FM]]/[[Vero Beach, Florida]] drops Conservative Talk for Country.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/86766/hot-country-on-way-to-vero-beach/ Hot Country Launches in Vero Beach] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|Up the road in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]], [[WGMW|WBXY]] and [[WXJZ]] swapped signals, as WBXY take over the 100.9 frequency, while a new format will take over the 99.5 frequency after New Year's Day.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/87038/gainesvilles-party-on-the-move/ Gainesville's Party On The Move] from Radio Insight (December 26, 2013)</ref> \n|-\n|[[CHFT-FM]] [[Fort McMurray, Alberta]] rebrands from 100.5 K-Rock to Cruz 100.5 FM\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''27'''\n|[[CKEA-FM]] [[Edmonton]] flips to classic hits (95.7 Cruz FM)\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|'''31'''\n|After 20 years of Classic Rock, [[KQBT|KKRW]]/[[Houston, Texas|Houston]] flips to R&B/Hip-Hop as \"93.7 The Beat.\" The move brings the format back to the same frequency when it was last used by KRLY from 1980 to 1982.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/87199/a-new-beat-in-houston/ 93.7 THE BEAT HOUSTON LAUNCHES] from Radio Insight (December 31, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|After 55 years at various stations in the [[Mohawk Valley]], Hank Brown will retire as \"your host for coffee and toast\" when he leaves his current position as morning host at [[WUSP (AM)|WUSP]].<ref>Naughton, Peter (December 2013). [http://www.cnyradio.com/2013/12/23/hank-brown-to-retire-at-years-end/ Hank Brown to retire at year's end]. ''CNYRadio.com''. Retrieved December 25, 2013.</ref>\n|}\n\n==Debuts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 2'''\n|[[CBS Sports Radio]] makes its launch across the United States. Most of the affiliates are primarily stations owned by CBS Radio and Cumulus Media outlets, as both groups are joint partners in this new venture.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/58594/cbs-sports-radio-network-to-debut-122013/ \"CBS Sports Radio Network To Debut 1/2/2013\"] from Radio Insight (June 21, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 20'''\n|[[Herman Cain]] will return to radio, hosting the program previously hosted by [[Neal Boortz]].\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''March 2'''\n|The program \"The Country Top 30 with Bobby Bones,\" hosted by [[Austin, Texas]], radio personality [[Bobby Bones (broadcaster)|Bobby Estell]] (aka Bobby Bones), debuts in syndication.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''August 19'''\n|Following a three-day [[Stunting (broadcasting)|stunt]] in which [[Patti Page]]'s \"[[Old Cape Cod]]\" was played on a loop, [[WKFY]]/[[East Harwich, Massachusetts]] (on [[Cape Cod]]) will launch with a format described by the station as \"[[oldies]], classic album cuts and modern artists loved by older listeners.\" WKFY will be targeted to listeners over 50.<ref name=cct-wkfylaunch>{{cite news|title=FM station Koffee to launch Monday|url=http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130817/BIZ/308170309&cid=sitesearch|accessdate=August 18, 2013|newspaper=[[Cape Cod Times]]|date=August 16, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130818211149/http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130817/BIZ/308170309&cid=sitesearch|archive-date=August 18, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''August 26'''\n|[[D.L. Hughley]] will make his foray in syndicated radio, as he debuts a daily program that will air on Urban AC stations.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84331/d-l-hughley-to-host-syndicated-afternoon-show/ \"D.L. Hughley To Host Syndicated Afternoon Show\"] from Radio Insight (August 18, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''September 30'''\n|[[Nickelodeon]] ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]) launches the [[iHeartRadio]] exclusive-''[[Nick Radio]]'' with [[Clear Channel Communications|Clear Channel Media and Entertainment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/85250/nickelodeon-joins-kids-radio-battle/|title=Nickelodeon Joins Kids Radio Battle|date=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''November 26'''\n|The [[Rhythmic adult contemporary|Rhythmic Hot AC]] format comes to Western [[Alabama]], as [[WLYB]]/[[Livingston, Alabama|Livingston]]-[[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]] signs on.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/124710/wylb-brings-rhythmic-ac-to-western-alabama WLYB Brings Rhythmic AC Format To Western Alabama] from All Access (November 27, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n==Closings==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 11'''\n|[[WIBX]]/[[Utica, New York]] ends its ''Sportswatch'' program, a long-running local broadcast that produced a large number of prominent sportscasters.<ref>[http://www.cnyradio.com/2013/01/16/former-wibx-hosts-offer-sportswatch-post-mortems/ Former WIBX hosts offer ''Sportswatch'' postmortems]. ''CNYRadio.com''. Retrieved January 18, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''February 7'''\n|After nearly 29 years of providing comedy programs and prep material to radio stations in the United States and Canada, as well as to international broadcasters, [[Dial Global]] pulls the plug on [[American Comedy Network]], stating that ACN \"wasn't viable any longer in terms of national coverage.\" <ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/115099/american-comedy-network-closes American Comedy Network Closes] from All Access (February 7, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''February 17'''\n|[[CJDL-FM|CKOT]]/[[Tillsonburg, Ontario]], the last [[daytimer|daytime-only station]] in Canada, signs off. Its programming will continue on [[CJDL-FM]], which had simulcast CKOT since 2007.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''March 20'''\n|In a surprise move amid the recent losses of high-profile Urban AC affiliates, [[Michael Baisden]] announced on his [[Facebook]] page that he will end his show on March 29 (even though he promises to come back in another form), but hours after he made that announcement Baisden learned that his syndicator [[Cumulus Media]] locked him and his staff out of his studios and started running repeats of his program until March 29, of which Baisden later responded \"In the words of [[Rodney King]], \u201cCan\u2019t we all get along?\u201d Just because we couldn\u2019t come to an agreement is no reason to deprive the listeners, our affiliates, and our advertisers of only 9 days to say goodbye and show our appreciation.\"<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/81247/michael-baisden-to-leave-his-syndicated-show/ \"Michael Baisden To Leave His Syndicated Show\"] from Radio Insight (March 20, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''April 15'''\n|[[Michael Smerconish]] leaves terrestrial radio, ending his nationally syndicated program on [[Dial Global]].\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May'''\n|(date unknown) [[WKZV (Pennsylvania)|WKZV]]/[[Washington, Pennsylvania]] signs off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbrtv.com/rumor-mill-wkzv-off-air-for-good/|title=Rumor Mill: WKZV off air for good|date=May 17, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 9'''\n|[[WUOW]]/[[Milford, New York|Milford]]-[[Oneonta, New York]] signs off after less than one year on air (although it was preceded by WUOW-LP, a low-power station that signed on in 2005).\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 23'''\n|[[WUTI]]/[[Utica, New York]] is vandalized and forced off the air.<ref>[http://www.cnyradio.com/2013/05/30/wuti-to-be-silent-for-weeks-after-vandals-hit-tower-site/ WUTI to be silent for weeks after vandals hit tower site].</ref> It never returned; its license was canceled by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] on August 11, 2014.<ref name=fcc-wutidefunct>{{cite web|last1=Doyle|first1=Peter H.|title=In re: WUTI(AM), Utica, NY|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=51787|website=CDBS Public Access|publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]]|accessdate=August 14, 2014|format=PDF|date=August 11, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 8'''\n|[[WVWZ|WQSV]]/[[Ashland City, Tennessee]] signs off due to a lack of local advertising support;<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/119083/wqsv-to-close-on-saturday WQSV To Close On Saturday] from All Access (June 5, 2013)</ref> the station's studio and transmitter site were sold in a foreclosure sale to Community Bank & Trust on June 14.<ref name=act-foreclosuresale>{{cite news|title=Bank buys radio station properties|url=http://www.tennessean.com/viewart/20130619/ASHLANDCITY01/306190061/Bank-buys-radio-station-properties|accessdate=June 23, 2013|newspaper=[[The Tennessean|The Ashland City Times]]|date=June 18, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 9'''\n|[[Nick Cannon]]'s weekly countdown program airs its last show.<ref>[http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/118801/as-nick-cannon-s-weekend-countdown-show-comes-to-a \"As Nick Cannon's Weekend Countdown Show Comes To An End, Rob Wagman Plots Something New\"] from All Access (May 28, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 27'''\n|The Monday through Thursday edition of ''[[Talk of the Nation]]'' ends its run on [[NPR]]. ''[[Science Friday]]'' will continue unaffected as a standalone program.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 30'''\n|[[Allen Hunt]] ends his radio program.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''July 19'''\n|[[Univision]] airs the final broadcast of [[Eddie \"Piol\u00edn\" Sotelo]]'s syndicated morning program \"Piol\u00edn Por La Mana\u00f1a.\" On July 22, the program is cancelled by Univision and all references related to his show are deleted from the company's corporate and radio station websites. His program (which originated from [[KSCA (FM)|KSCA]]/Los Angeles) has been replaced with music programming at his former affiliates.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84289/univision-cancels-piolin/ \"Univision Cancels Piolin\"] from Radio Insight (July 22, 2013)</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''September 6'''\n|[[Talk Radio Network]] shuts down its ''America's Radio News Network'' [[all-news radio]] service. The entirety of the network's weekday lineup leaves the network by the end of the year.<ref>Fybush, Scott (September 9, 2013). [http://www.fybush.com/nerw-992013-another-flip-at-buffalos-kb/ Another flip at Buffalo's KB]. ''NorthEast Radio Watch''. Retrieved September 12, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''October 7'''\n|[[KTDK]]/[[Sanger, Texas]], formerly the simulcast of [[KTCK (AM)|KTCK SportsRadio 1310 The Ticket]], has ceased operations. Owner [[Cumulus Media]] has surrendered this station's license the following week.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''November 18'''\n|A contract dispute forces the abrupt cancellation of ''[[The War Room with Quinn and Rose]]''.<ref>[http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/tv-radio/2013/11/18/Conservative-hosts-Jim-Quinn-Rose-Tennent-out-at-WPGB/stories/201311180151 Conservative hosts Jim Quinn, Rose Tennent out at WPGB]. ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''. Retrieved November 19, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''December 3'''\n|After a 15-year run, the message board Radio Discussions (originally Radio-Info until May) is shut down.<ref>[http://rbr.com/radio-discussions-shuts-down/ Radio Discussions shuts down] from RBR (December 3, 2013)</ref> \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''December 20'''\n|[[John R. Gambling]] will retire from radio. Gambling's [[Rambling with Gambling|morning-drive radio program in New York City]] had run near-continuously for 88 years and had previously been hosted by his father and grandfather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2013/11/radio-host-john-gambling-to-retire/|title=Radio Host John Gambling to Retire|date=November 11, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''December 31'''\n|Cumulus Media will end the syndicated programs hosted by [[Geraldo Rivera]] and [[Mike Huckabee]]. Rivera's show will become a local broadcast in the same midday timeslot at flagship [[WABC (AM)|WABC]]/[[New York City]] starting January 1, 2014; [[Dennis Miller]] (acquired in Cumulus's acquisition of Dial Global) will fill the two hosts' place in the Cumulus syndicated lineup.<ref>[http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/86781/geraldo-to-go-local-on-wabc-depart-syndication/ GERALDO TO GO LOCAL ON WABC; DEPART SYNDICATION] from Radio Insight (November 25, 2013)</ref>\n|}\n\n==Deaths==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Person\n! Age\n! Notability\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''January 11'''\n| [[Jimmy O'Neill (DJ)|Jimmy O'Neill]]\n| 72\n| Disc jockey (credits include KQV/Pittsburgh, WCAE/Pittsburgh, KRLA/Los Angeles, KFWB/San Francisco, KDAY/Redondo Beach)\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''February 1'''\n| [[Ed Koch]]\n| 88\n| [[Mayor of New York City]] from 1977 to 1989; host of a weekly radio program on [[WBBR]]/New York\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''March 6'''\n| [[Stompin' Tom Connors]]\n| 77\n| Canadian radio host ([[CKGB]]/[[Timmins]]) and country/folk musician\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''April 16'''\n| [[Pat Summerall]]\n| 82\n| American radio and television host and football commentator (radio credits include morning host at [[WCBS (AM)|WCBS]]/New York from 1966 to 1969 and at various times color commentator and studio host for ''[[NFL on Dial Global|NFL on CBS Radio]]'')\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''April 26'''\n| [[George Jones]]\n| 81\n| American country musician (hosted a show on [[KCOX]]/[[Jasper, Texas]] from 1947 to 1949), staple of the [[classic country]] format\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 11'''\n| [[Arnold Peters (actor)|Arnold Peters]]\n| 87\n| English actor, who played Jack Woolley in ''The Archers'' soap opera for 31 years.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 13'''\n| [[Joyce Brothers]]\n| 85\n| American psychologist who hosted the first ever radio program to dispense psychological advice\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''May 25'''\n| [[Gene Burns]]\n| 72\n| American libertarian talk radio host ([[WHHO|WHHG]]/[[Hornell, New York]], [[WCBM]]/[[Baltimore]], [[WEEI (AM)|WEEI]]/[[Boston]], [[WKIS-AM|WKIS]]/[[Orlando, Florida]], [[WCAU Radio|WCAU]]/[[Philadelphia]], [[WRKO]]/Boston, [[WOR (AM)|WOR]]/[[New York City]], [[KGO (AM)|KGO]]/[[San Francisco]])\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 5'''\n| [[Don Bowman (singer)|Don Bowman]]\n| 75\n| Disc jockey at several radio stations in the central United States (including [[KRZK]] in [[Branson, Missouri]]), comedian and original host of ''[[American Country Countdown]]''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''June 28'''\n|Jim Nayder\n|59\n|Program director for [[WBEZ]]/[[Chicago]]; host of WBEZ's ''Magnificent Obsession'' and [[NPR]]'s ''Annoying Music Show''<ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-jim-nayder-host-of-the-annoying-music-show-dead-20130628,0,6186296.column Obituary for Jim Nayder] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017033014/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-jim-nayder-host-of-the-annoying-music-show-dead-20130628,0,6186296.column |date=2013-10-17 }} from ''Chicago Tribune'', 6/28/2013</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''July 27'''\n|[[Kidd Kraddick]]\n|53\n|American radio and television personality, host of the syndicated ''[[Kidd Kraddick in the Morning]]'' show.<ref name=\"nyt130728\">{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |location=[[New York City]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |title=David \u2018Kidd\u2019 